<doc id="645602" wikidata="Q913849" url="?curid=645602" title="Minimax theorem">
<text>In the mathematical area of game theory and of convex optimization, a minimax theorem is a theorem that claims that
: formula_1
under certain conditions on the sets formula_2 and formula_3 and on the function formula_4. It is always true that the left-hand side is at most the right-hand side (max–min inequality) but equality only holds under certain conditions identified by minimax theorems. The first theorem in this sense is von Neumann&#x27;s minimax theorem about two-player zero-sum games published in 1928, which is considered the starting point of game theory. Von Neumann is quoted as saying &quot;As far as I can see, there could be no theory of games ... without that theorem ... I thought there was nothing worth publishing until the Minimax Theorem was proved&quot;. Since then, several generalizations and alternative versions of von Neumann&#x27;s original theorem have appeared in the literature.

== Bilinear functions and zero-sum games ==
Von Neumann&#x27;s original theorem was motivated by game theory and applies to the case where 

* formula_2 and formula_3 are standard simplexes: formula_7 and formula_8, and
* formula_9 is a linear function in both of its arguments (that is, formula_4 is bilinear) and therefore can be written formula_11 for a finite matrix formula_12, or equivalently as formula_13.

Under these assumptions, von Neumann proved that
: formula_14
In the context of two-player zero-sum games, the sets formula_2 and formula_3 correspond to the strategy sets of the first and second player, respectively, which consist of lotteries over their actions (so-called mixed strategies), and their payoffs are defined by the payoff matrix formula_17. The function formula_9 encodes the expected value of the payoff to the first player when the first player plays the strategy formula_19 and the second player plays the strategy formula_20.

== Concave-convex functions ==

Von Neumann&#x27;s minimax theorem can be generalized to domains that are compact and convex, and to functions that are concave in their first argument and convex in their second argument (known as concave-convex functions). Formally, let formula_21 and formula_22 be compact convex sets. If formula_23 is a continuous function that is concave-convex, i.e.

: formula_24 is concave for every fixed formula_25, and
: formula_26 is convex for every fixed formula_27.

Then we have that

: formula_28

== Sion&#x27;s minimax theorem ==

Sion&#x27;s minimax theorem is a generalization of von Neumann&#x27;s minimax theorem due to Maurice Sion, relaxing the requirement that It states:

Let formula_2 be a convex subset of a linear topological space and let formula_3 be a compact convex subset of a linear topological space. If formula_4 is a real-valued function on formula_32 with

: formula_33 upper semicontinuous and quasi-concave on formula_2, for every fixed formula_35, and
: formula_36 lower semicontinuous and quasi-convex on formula_3, for every fixed formula_38.

Then we have that

: formula_39

